# Token Efficiency (AI Sessions)

Minimize **tokens spent in chat and tool output** without lowering code quality. Applies to every AI-assisted task in every project.

---

## The Rule

Optimize for **fewer tokens**, not for less work. Correctness, exploration, and implementation quality are non-negotiable.

---

## Responses

- **Bullets only** - what changed, why (one line each), how to verify.
- No filler, recap of the prompt, or step-by-step narration of actions already taken.
- No restating file contents the user can open; cite paths, not walls of code in chat.
- Use line-range code citations only when they aid a decision; skip decorative quotes.
- Do not volunteer follow-ups every message; ask only when blocked or a choice is required.

---

## Code Changes

- **Smallest correct diff** - prefer surgical edits over rewriting whole files.
- **MUST align** every file you open or edit with applicable rules (`naming.md`, `code-patterns.md`, etc.) - fix violations in scope; no repo-wide drive-by renames or refactors.
- **No verbose comments** - code should be self-explanatory; comment only non-obvious business logic (see `code-formatting.md` - token-efficiency wins for comment policy).
- **No drive-by refactors** unrelated to the task.
- Match existing conventions; reuse helpers instead of duplicating logic.

---

## Tool Use (Save Round-Trips, Not Rigor)

- **Targeted exploration**: read/search what you need; do not re-read the same file unless it changed.
- **Parallelize** independent reads, greps, and searches in one turn when possible.
- **Do not skip exploration** when behavior, architecture, or edge cases are unclear.
- Prefer exact search (`grep` / `glob`) for known symbols; use semantic search when location is unknown.
- Avoid dumping large command outputs or full file reads into the reply - summarize findings.
- If the project has a formatter/linter, run it on **touched files** - do not manually reformat whole files for style-only churn.

---

## What NOT to Cut

- Investigation required to implement or fix correctly.
- Tests, types, and error handling when required by `testing.md` or the user.
- Commit/PR messages when requested - complete sentences, no padding.

---

## Conflicts

If this conflicts with "be verbose in chat" elsewhere, **this rule wins for chat**. Commits and PRs stay clear and complete when requested.

